                <head>328. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On the morning of September 23, General <persName corresp="#p_CGF2">Fuad
                        Chehab</persName> took the oath of office as President of Lebanon in
                    Parliament and delivered an inaugural address appealing for national unity, a
                    healing of wounds, the redressing of the national economy, and the
                    reestablishment of cordial relations with Arab states in particular and friendly
                    nations in general. (Telegram 1668 from Beirut, September 23; Department of
                    State, Central Files, 783A.11/9–2358) On September 24, President <persName
                        corresp="#p_CGF2">Chehab</persName> announced a cabinet that included Prime
                    Minister Rachid Karame, who also held the portfolios of Interior and National
                    Defense, Finance Minister Rafik Naja, Minister of Foreign Affairs Philip Takla,
                    Minister of National Economy and Information Charles Helou, Minister of Justice
                    and Social Affairs Joseph Sauda, Minister of Education and Health Mohammed
                    Safieddine, Minister of Agriculture Fuad Najjar, and Minister of Public Works
                    Farid Trad. (Telegram 1690 from Beirut, September 25; <hi rend="italic"
                        >ibid.,</hi> 783A.13/9–2558)</p>
            </div>
